title: For Sale:  Fully Processed (Trimmed/Chamferred/Deburred) AND Primed .223/5.56 Brass - x1082 Pieces!
postcontent:
You are purchasing >1000 Piece of Once-Fired (Approx 90% was fired from my own AR-15) .223/5.56 brass. I recently stopped reloading and this is what I had prepped already so I could just throw in some powder and a bullet and go. This is fully processed once-fired brass. Everything was run through a Small-Base .223 reloading die so they would chamber for an AR-15. They were trimmed with a Lee Trimmer and chamfered/deburred using my Lyman Case Prep Xpress machine. I used a VLD chamfer on the inside so bullets slide in much easier without ripping the plating. This is brass that I use for my AR-15 accuracy runs, not some quick cheap processing so I could turn around and resell them. 

Primed: These are primed with CCI #450 Small Magnum Rifle Primers. These are one of the best to use because they are hard to prevent detonation from the BCG due to the firing pin in an AR-15 going into battery and touching the primer. If you reload for AR-15s pay attention to this. There are very few primers like the AR-15 Federal Match primers or these that anyone recommends for an AR platform.

All of the brass has been divided by headstamp. 95% is Lake City, year 09/10/11/13/14. There are a little under 100 of FC/PMC.

Pricing: Current market puts 1000 once-fired military brass around $75 Shipped. The primers were approx $38 after tax. I'd like to get $80. I would consider that highly fair considering the amount of hours of prep and the care that was taken on these cases.

Brand new carrier, elastic, etc. Comes with a surplus Monarch Level II blunt trauma pad 5'' x 8'' for the front pouch. Vented sides. 3/4 of an inch gap between front and back for ventilation during hotter months. Bought it because the IIIA is a full wrap and it gets too hot in the summer.

Will fit a medium sized guy. I have a 38'' chest and a 37'' in stomach and the elastic is in it's normal default position. Plenty of room to go either way. Larger guys may lose some coverage on the sides. Really big dudes should probably buy a bigger vest. Remember optimal vest position is to cover the lung, the spare lung and the heart as well as a few of the other internal organs. Mine is sized to come to just above the belly button while standing so I can draw my sidearm, magazines etc. I am 5' 10'' / 170 lbs.

Vest has been worn once. I could send it back to Bulletproofme for a full refund but I'd rather it go to a local, law-abiding citizen who needs some protection.

Selling because my wife surprised me with a brand new Point Blank IIIA vest with vented sides for my birthday. No longer have any use for this one.

If you are unsure whether NIJ Level II meets your requirements I recommend looking it up. 

You could go to Bulletproofme.com and buy this exact set up for $220+$25 Trauma Pad +$20 shipping. And then wait for it to arrive. All respect to Bulletproofme but I'd rather save $80 and get it immediately.

Remember this is BULLET RESISTANT. This will not turn you into Iron Man. High caliber weapons can still penetrate. Multiple hits can penetrate. Something weird could happen and a bullet could penetrate. Wearing body armor is not a guarantee of survival. By purchasing you acknowledge this and accept all liability for what might happen if you get into a firefight.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Taurus TCP 380 (PT738) - .380 ACP pocket carry
postcontent:
Almost NIB Taurus TCP 380 (Model PT738) with less than 50 rounds through it.  I bought it two weeks ago along with a Ruger LCP to compare them and choose which one to keep.  Both of them have worked flawlessly and it’s been a tough decision but the LCP feels just a little better in MY hand so I’ve decided to sell this one.

This is a polymer frame gun…very light and it’s easy to make it disappear in any pocket.  The Taurus TCP has one major feature which the LCP doesn’t have and that’s last-round-slide-hold-open. When the last round in a mag is fired, the slide locks open telling you the Taurus TCP mag is empty.

The TCP is an outstanding pocket-carry design with a very smooth trigger. Its light weight (10.2 oz.) with a comfortable grip makes it an outstanding concealed carry gun. It's easy to pocket carry and just disappears in your pocket or purse.  It’s identical in size to the Ruger LCP but feels a bit softer to shoot than the LCP.

The full package comes with everything that came with the gun from the factory: original box, Taurus locking system with keys, all paperwork, and the 6-round magazine supplied by Taurus.

I’m also including an extra factory 6-round mag that I had purchased.

The serial number begins with “513...” and ends with “E” indicating this is a recently manufactured gun.  The Taurus lifetime warranty travels with the gun, not just the original owner.

I prefer face-to-face transfer in east Tennessee without shipping. Must be a legal buyer, 21 or over with valid TN driver’s license or permit.

If I don’t respond to your email immediately, it only means I’m at work and I’ll respond soon after I get home. If the ad is still up, the gun is still available.

I’d like a cash sale but I'll also consider a trade for a .22lr handgun or a double-barrel 20 gauge shotgun in decent shape.  Let me know what you have.

Sorry, but I’m not looking for low-ball offers. Thanks!

title: For Sale:  Yildiz SPZ 12 ME Over/Under 12 gauge shotgun with 5 factory chokes and 2 Brimley Skeet Chokes
postcontent:
I have for sale a lightly used Yildiz SPZ 12 ME shotgun.  These guns are made in Turkey and imported through Briley and Academy Sports and Outdoors in Texas.   For warranty claims and repairs, the guns are sent to Briley in Texas where American gunsmiths work on them. 

I purchased this gun new in October 2014 for $430 from Academy.  I've fired 100 rounds through it on the trap field, and it handles quite nicely.  It has no cosmetic flaws and, other than the shortened stock, looks brand new. 

The action on this particular gun has been polished and properly lubricated to ensure smooth and easy function (not as smooth as a Beretta, but at 1/6 the price, it is perfectly pleasant).  If you've handled one of these off-the-rack, you'll know that the action is unpleasantly stiff when they're brand new (and if you didn't know that, be forewarned:  off the rack, these things are atrocious and really need work).    This particular gun has had these issues resolved, and is field-ready.  The gun is fitted with a walnut stock and handguard.  

The receiver is aluminum, so this shotgun is lightweight, and kicks like it.  I had a professional gunsmith shorten the length of pull by 1.5 inches, and install a Limbsaver recoil pad. 

If you're a serious clay shooter or bird hunter, you'll probably scoff at these imported Turkish guns, but if you are just looking to add a good-looking and functional O/U 12 gauge to your collection, this is a tremendous value (especially with the action work and customization). 

Shotgun is sold with two Briley Skeet Tubes installed ($40-value/each)
This shotgun also includes the 5 factory choke tubes (ranging from Cylinder to Full).

Prices are for cash, and are firm. 

Will meet face-to-face in Atlanta area, or ship via FFL at your cost.

title: For Sale:  Original SOG Trident Bowie
postcontent:
I have the original version (not 2.0) of the SOG Trident Bowie. It has been stored for many years and I'd like to get rid of it and buy something I'll use. When I first bought it I dropped it getting into my truck and it landed on the very butt of the handle and just marred the end of the handle a little but the knife was in the sheath so everything else is fine. Knife blade is flawless as it was literally never used. I will post pictures soon. 
I can meet in Plano area if you want to look at it and are serious about purchasing. 

Asking $250 OBO. 

See the link from SOG's website: 

http://www.sogknivescollectors.com/trident-s2-bowie.php 

Rarity Details: Last Known MSRP: $ Production dates: 1986? - 2004 Production numbers: ? Limited run?: No. Other things of interest: One of the first few models off SOG's production line. 3 versions of the knife were produced. 

Rarity index: 8.5/10 (10 being the most rare)

Rarity index scale (1 to 10, 10 being the most rare): 1 - Very common; easily available on ebay, google product search and almost every knife selling website. Spammed with at least 10+ listings on ebay. 3 - Has been around for at least 2 years and are selling reasonably well, with retailers favouring other newer models over this knife. 5 - Knives that are on the borderline of being discontinued or have been discontinued for less than 6 months 6 - Products from 6 onwards are either discontinued or limited edition. 7 - Discontinued knives that pop up once every few months on the "For Sale" part of forums or on ebay. Still can be found at a few online shops though. 8 - Knives that need lots of researching to find. Not available anymore in online knife shops and pop up (if you're lucky) >4 months for one at a time. 9 - Knives holding this rarity are the shadowy kind. You can't find any information on them at all (not even from online knife shops that have not taken down that knife's product page). If you see one for sale grab at all cost. 10 - The rarest of all knives. If you hadn't been here you wouldn't even have known that it existed. Should you have one of these you better lock it up in a triple-combination safe and treat it like a family heirloom...
